    <discussion>Dysphania botrys is related to a species from Africa and southern Eurasia, D.
        schraderiana (Schultes) Mosyakin &amp; Clemants, which may occur locally in North America as
        introduced. Dysphania schraderiana has distinctly keeled perianth segments with mostly
        sessile or subsessile glands. The general inflorescence in D. schraderiana is usually leafy
        almost to the top, distal cauline leaves are similar to proximal ones (in D. botrys distal
        leaves are normally much reduced, and the distal portion of the general inflorescence
        appears nearly leafless). H. A. Wahl (1954) reported that D. schraderiana (as Chenopodium
        schraderianum) had been grown in Ontario. He did not indicate that it had
        escaped.</discussion>
